Gustaw Mazurek - MS-DOS/Windows version
e-mail: @{fg shine}gustaw47@poczta.onet.pl@{fg text}

@ENDNODE
///
/// Supported chipsets
@NODE CHIP "Supported chipsets"

    @{b}@{u}Supported chipsets@{uu}@{ub}


COMBO2 programmer in conjunction with this software lets you programming
following chipsets:

 ·  Atmel '51 20-PIN : 89C1051, 89C2051, 89C4051.
 ·  Atmel '51 40-PIN : AT89C51, AT89C52, AT89S53, AT89C55, AT89S8252,
	AT89C55WD, AT89C51RC, T89C51RC2-16, T89C51RC2-32, T89C51RD2

 · AVR : AT90S1200, AT90S2313, AT90S2323, AT90S2343, AT90S85x5,
	ATiny12, ATiny15, ATmega103, ATmega128

 · PIC : 16C84, 16F84, 16F83, 16F870, 16F872, 16F873, 16F874, 16F876,
	16F877, 12C508, 12C509, 16C505, 16F627, 16F628, 16C54C,
	16C58, 16C622, 16C73, 16C66

 · EEPROM : 24C02, 24C04, 24C08, 24C16, 24C32, 24C64, 24C128, 24C256,
	93C46, 93C56, 93C66, 93C57, 93C06, 93S46, 93S56, 93S66,
	93C76, 93C86, 24LC00, 24C01, 24C01A,
	SDE2506, 25C010, 25C020, 25C040, 25C080, 25C160, 25C320,
	25C640, AT25128, AT25256


 ·  There is also possibility to add next chipsets from above groups
    (programme is still under development).

@ENDNODE
///
/// Installation
@NODE INST "Installation"

    @{b}@{u}Software installation@{uu}@{ub}


COMBO2 software doesn't require installation process. You need to unpack
archive after downloading and... run the programme :)

@ENDNODE
///
/// Configuration
@NODE CONF "Configuration"

    @{b}@{u}Configuration@{uu}@{ub}


You can change programme configuration in configuration window.

Meanings of all fields:
(default values given in brackets)

Font          : name of font used by GUI (TopazPL.font)
Size          : font size used by GUI (9)
Change        : opens a requester, allowing you to choose font and its size
System font   : enabling this fild will result in programme using current system
                font for GUI
Driver        : RS232 communication port name (serial.device)
RS port to use: you can choose if the programme use RS232 port on main board
                of A400/A1200 or other port/board (see @{"chapter 5" link comm})
Initial speed : initial communication speed (57600 or 19200 bodes)
Working speed : speed while working with programmer (57600)

@{i}Attention:
*) In case of having poor configuration you can start communication with
   programmer using 19200 bodes by shortcutting pins 1 and 2 together in 
   DIL40 socket [and set @{u}Initial speed@{uu} to 19200] and set desired
   @{u}Working speed@{uu} [57600, 28800, 19200, 14400, 9600, 4800, 2400, 1200].
@{ui}

@ENDNODE
///
/// Usage
@NODE USAG "Usage"

    @{b}@{u}Usage@{uu}@{ub}


You can invoke options from following menus:
    · File - is used to open/write/edit data for programmer
    · Chipset - here you can choose desired chipset on which you will work later
    · Operation - here you can choose type of operation, for example 'Programming'
    · Help - a few words of information about possible operations

Following operations are available:
    · Read - reads content of chipset
    · Programming - writes file to chipset
    · Verify - compares content of chipset with choosen file
    · Blank check - checks if chipset's memory is clear
    · Clear - clears chipset memory
    · Signature - tries to identify chipset plugged into programmer

Beside menus, you can also use buttons, which let you easy select desired operation.

@ENDNODE
///
/// How to programme chipset
@NODE PROG "How to programme a chipset"

    @{b}@{u}How to programme a chipset@{uu}@{ub}


To programme a chipset you should:

  1. Connect programmer to communication port.
  2. Connect programmer to power supply adaptor.
  3. Run the programme.
  4. Choose a chipset from 'Chipset' menu (or use "Signature" option
     after step 5 and 6).
  5. Change (if needed) communication port.
  6. Place chipset in socket.
  7. Choose programme file (Menu FLASH/Open or EEPROM/Open).
  8. Choose 'Programming' option.

@ENDNODE
///
/// Something doesn't work...
@NODE PROB "Something doesn't work..."

    @{b}@{u}Something doesn't work...@{uu}@{ub}


Authors of that system make all possible efforts to delivier software
working without any problems.
But when something doesn't work:

 · Check power supply (proper voltage is indicated by green LED).
 · Check connection of programmer to communication port.
 · If  everything is OK use @{"Tester2" LINK TES2} programme (included in the
   package).
 · If Tester2 shows  that programmer works properly, that  means something
   is wrong with software.
 · Try to use different version of COMBO software and contact the author
   (you can  find e-mail addresses in @{"requirements" LINK REQU} section)
   giving full explanation of conditions in which that bug happened (hardware
   configuration is of special interest).

@ENDNODE
///
/// Comments to Combo3 hardware
@NODE COMM "Comments to Combo3 hardware"

    @{b}@{u}Comments to Combo3 hardware@{uu}@{ub}


New version of hardware - Combo3 - uses RTS signal line of serial communication
port to indicate voltage supplying chipsets in programmer.
Due to no possibility of proper interaction by system with that signal on
communication port, Combo2 programme writes @{u}directly to CIA register@{uu}
(if only "RS port to use" option is set to "int. A1200/A400"). You must switch
this option to "any" if hardware communicates not by means of that port (in
case of e.g. AmigaOne or Pegasos).

Because of used hardware solutions proper handling of AT89C55WD chipset by Combo3
connected to other than internal Amiga serial port is not possible (on current
stage).
Furthermore, it is also recommended (for mentioned RS ports) leaving RTS
line unconnected to Combo3 programmer, due to appearing 6.25V on that line
(value of power for RTS="0") or making a switch controlling transfer of RTS line
state information.
To make programmer work properly in such case, after choosing option "any", you
will be informed about every single need of changing RTS line state.

@ENDNODE
///
/// Tester2 - when something doesn't work properly...
@NODE TES2 "Tester2 - when something doesn't work properly..."

    @{b}@{u}Tester2 - when something doesn't work properly...@{uu}@{ub}


To make running/testing programmer easier (for users who build programmers
themselves) additional programme has been prepared: Tester2. This programme
lets you check if programmer works properly.
Available options:

 - RST, VPP, LED, P32 ... P37 : sets particular outs of U10
 - I2C start, I2C stop : initializes/deinitializes ISP port
 - Read D0..D7 : reads data from chipset
 - Write D0..D7 : writes data to chipset
 - Write A0..A15 : sets address to read/write options
 - RST=H, RST=L : controls power value by RST line @{"(see chapter 5)" LINK COMM}
 - Read sig. : sets outs of U10 to reads chipset signature
 - Read code : sets outs of U10 to reads programme code from chipset
 - Write code : writes value to programmed chipset
 - Inc. address : increases current address by 1
 - Reset : resets all settings of Combo programmer

Note:
The programme configuration depends on Combo2 configuration, as it reads
Combo2 config file. Hence both programmes work with same fonts, same RS port
and parameters of communication.

@ENDNODE
